The discovery of the tumulus was announced on {{ill|December 9, 2010|JA|12月9日|qq=draft}}, and it is situated adjacent to the {{ill|Kengoshizuka Kofun|ja|牽牛子塚古墳|qq=draft}}. Based on descriptions in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft}}, it is believed to be the probable burial site of {{ill|Princess Ōta|ja|大田皇女|qq=draft}}, a member of the Imperial family from the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft}}.
== Discovery == [[File:Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, 3D-B.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Overhead view of the stone chamber}}]] [[File:Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Expanded view of the stone chamber}}]] In mid-October 2010, during the process of backfilling the excavation site around the Kengoshizuka Kofun, {{ill|Shinji Saikō|ja|西光慎治|qq=draft}}, a technician with the Asuka Village Board of Education, noticed a one-meter stone buried approximately 20 meters southeast of the Kengoshizuka Kofun. The stone showed clear evidence of human modification, prompting further excavation that led to the discovery of the Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101214104644/http://www.iza.ne.jp/news/newsarticle/natnews/topics/472754/ "Unexpected Major Discovery Near Kengoshizuka Kofun"], Sankei Shimbun, December 9, 2010. Accessed December 2010.</ref>
== Response from the Imperial Household Agency == Despite the discovery of the Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft}} has not revised its designation of the tumulus near the {{ill|Kuramoki no Misasagi|ja|車木ケンノウ古墳|qq=draft}} (currently identified by the agency as the mausoleum of {{ill|Empress Saimei|ja|斉明天皇|qq=draft}}) as the burial site of Ōta no Himemiko. The agency cites discrepancies between the archaeological findings and the Nihon Shoki's account, which states that {{ill|Emperor Tenji|ja|天智天皇|qq=draft}} did not impose forced labor on the populace to construct the stone chamber.<ref>[http://mainichi.jp/enta/art/news/20101210ddm012040038000c.html "Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun: Discovered as Described in the Nihon Shoki; Debate Over Imperial Mausoleum Designations Accelerates"], Mainichi Shimbun, December 10, 2010. Accessed December 2010.</ref>
== Cultural Properties == === National Historic Site === * '''Kengoshizuka Kofun and Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun''' - In 2014 (Heisei 26), the previously designated Historic Site "Kengoshizuka Kofun" was expanded to include the Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, and the designation was renamed "Kengoshizuka Kofun and Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun."<ref>{{国指定文化財等データベース|401|1945|牽牛子塚古墳・越塚御門古墳}}</ref>
