'''Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun''' (越塚御門古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|en|Kofun|qid=Q1141225|lt=Kofun|1=Kofun}} located in {{ill|Asuka, Nara|en|Asuka, Nara|qid=Q752397|lt=Asuka, Nara|1=Asuka, Nara}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en|Nara Prefecture|qid=Q131287|lt=Nara Prefecture|1=Nara Prefecture}}, Japan. It has been designated a {{ill|Historic site|en|Historic site|qid=Q1081138|lt=Historic site of Japan|1=Historic site}}}.

The discovery of the tumulus was announced on {{ill|December 9, 2010|JA|12月9日|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 9, 2010|1=December 9|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q2304}}, and it is situated adjacent to the {{ill|Kengoshizuka Kofun|en|Kengoshizuka Kofun|qid=Q11571102|lt=Kengoshizuka Kofun|1=Kengoshizuka Kofun}}. Based on descriptions in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|qid=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}}, it is believed to be the probable burial site of {{ill|Princess Ōta|en|Princess Ōta|qid=Q603057|lt=Princess Ōta|1=Princess Ōta}}, a member of the Imperial family from the {{ill|Asuka period|en|Asuka period|qid=Q210688|lt=Asuka period|1=Asuka period}}.

== Discovery ==
[[File:Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, 3D-B.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Overhead view of the stone chamber}}]]
[[File:Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Expanded view of the stone chamber}}]]
In mid-October 2010, during the process of backfilling the excavation site around the Kengoshizuka Kofun, {{ill|Shinji Saikō|ja|西光慎治|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinji Saikō|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a technician with the Asuka Village Board of Education, noticed a one-meter stone buried approximately 20 meters southeast of the Kengoshizuka Kofun. The stone showed clear evidence of human modification, prompting further excavation that led to the discovery of the Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101214104644/http://www.iza.ne.jp/news/newsarticle/natnews/topics/472754/ "Unexpected Major Discovery Near Kengoshizuka Kofun"], Sankei Shimbun, December 9, 2010. Accessed December 2010.</ref>

== Response from the Imperial Household Agency ==
Despite the discovery of the Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|en|Imperial Household Agency|qid=Q1143602|lt=Imperial Household Agency|1=Imperial Household Agency}} has not revised its designation of the tumulus near the {{ill|Kuramoki no Misasagi|ja|車木ケンノウ古墳|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuramoki no Misasagi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (currently identified by the agency as the mausoleum of {{ill|Empress Kōgyoku|en|Empress Kōgyoku|qid=Q235296|lt=Empress Saimei|1=Empress Kōgyoku}}) as the burial site of Ōta no Himemiko. The agency cites discrepancies between the archaeological findings and the Nihon Shoki's account, which states that {{ill|Emperor Tenji|en|Emperor Tenji|qid=Q314802|lt=Emperor Tenji|1=Emperor Tenji}} did not impose forced labor on the populace to construct the stone chamber.<ref>[http://mainichi.jp/enta/art/news/20101210ddm012040038000c.html "Koshi Tsukagomon Kofun: Discovered as Described in the Nihon Shoki; Debate Over Imperial Mausoleum Designations Accelerates"], Mainichi Shimbun, December 10, 2010. Accessed December 2010.</ref>

